status_message: Trump leaped to the conclusion that all 122 detainees mentioned in the Fox & Friends report were released by President Obama. They weren't. In fact, according to the Director of National Intelligence's website, President Bush released 532 detainees from Guantanamo Bay, and 113 of those former detainees returned to "the battlefield." Meanwhile, Obama released 161 detainees, with just nine returning to the battlefield. So, no, Obama didn't release 122 "vicious prisoners" from Gitmo who returned to terrorism. He released 161, but only nine of them rejoined al-Qaeda.

status_message:
In less than a week, Donald Trump will be our (illegitimate) president. Already, the Democrats and the entire progressive movement are plotting to remove him from office and oppose every single thing he does. He is not our president and -will- be a one term (more likely less than one) office holder.

The parallels to the right wing freak out over the election of Barack Obama are undeniable. The anger. The hatred. The fear. They all seem similar. But they're not. Those similarities are superficial.

I cannot stress this enough: The right lost its mind over the election of a black man -because- he was a black man. That's it. Full stop. Women were crying hysterically about losing "their" country because of the color of his skin and nothing else. Yes, Republicans screeched that he was a Muslim Socialist terrorist blablabla but nothing in his background suggested that he would do the kind of damage that he was accused of planning. And nothing he did in office lived up to his alleged plans to destroy America.

Obama was a left of center pragmatic politician that was handed an economy on the brink of collapse and he fixed it, carefully and methodically. Along the way, he increased social equality and helped millions of Democratic voters get healthcare. And he helped even -more- Republican voters get it as well because he didn't care who you voted for. If you needed help, he tried to help you.

The right foamed at the mouth over the color of the president's skin and listened to not a single word he said or deed he accomplished.

On the other hand, Trump has spewed hatred and racism and bigotry and sexism every single day of his campaign and his transition. He will continue to spew it as president. He has promised to tear apart families, bring back torture, take revenge on his political enemies, undermine the Constitution, give the police the ability to murder minorities with impunity, and he has brought white nationalism into mainstream politics. Actual Nazis are excited to be able to live out their darkest fantasies under Trump. Nazis. Real ones.

And all that is BEFORE we even get to the specter of this being the single most corrupt administration in American history. And BEFORE we even get to the fact that Russia assaulted our election. And BEFORE we even get to the fact that Trump is a sexual predator and deviant. And BEFORE we even get to the mountain of blackmail material that exists because of this deviancy.

So when the left plots to destroy Trump and when we express our hatred of everything he stands for, do not mistake it for the mindless, baseless rage that was hurled at Obama. Ours is based in reality. We are faced not with the loss of white privilege and white hegemony, we are faced with an existential threat to our democracy, our rights, our morality and our safety. We know this because this is what Trump has told us he is going to do.

"When someone shows you who they are, believe them the first time." ~ Maya Angelou

We went from one of the smartest, most competent and most dedicated presidents in American history to a screeching sideshow freak that flings poop from his gilded cage. We all know the election was not legitimate and that Trump is an unqualified, garish pretender to the throne. This will not stand and Republicans will come to see the fraudulent election of 2016 as the very definition of a Pyrrhic victory. For when Trump falls as he inevitably must, he will take them with him, screaming into the abyss of history's harsh judgement.

You can scoff now as you wallow in your illegitimate victory and insist that racism has come to stay but you're fooling yourself. There's not enough of you angry bigots to hold on to this country and there's less of you every day. There's far more of us, the diverse and the open-minded, than there are of you and we will not be stopped. The Resistance is real. The Resistance has already begun.

status_message:
I have to admit, I have zero confidence the Electoral College will do anything other than vote the way their state won. I would LIKE for them to pick a different Republican, one less insane, but I just don't see it happening.

Some will vote because they actually like Trump. Some will vote because they're afraid to go against the voters. Others are simply afraid for their lives because Trump's Brownshirts have made it clear they will visit violence upon dissent.

At this point, my best hope is just enough of them snub Trump that the House has to pick the president. House Republicans will be faced with an impossible choice:

1. Pick someone they would prefer like Kasich. This is will infuriate Trump's white nationalist followers and Republicans will be massacred in the midterms. Kasich will almost certainly be a one term president. BUT, they would be able to push through all of the extremist agenda they want without having to worry about Trump starting a war with China.

2. Cave in to fear and pick Trump anyway. This option is potentially worse because when Trump becomes a historical disaster that ends in disgrace, Republicans will be unable to distance themselves from him. After all, THEY picked him to be president.

But, as I said, I don't see enough electors having the balls to vote against Trump. Yet, if even a dozen or so break with their party, it will still undermine Trump's presidency. He already has no mandate whatsoever and producing a number of faithless electors would weaken him even further and that's good for the country in the long run.
Even Alec Baldwin was in on this one. He's there for a split second, so don't blink or you'll miss him.

status_message:
Three types of liberals will be watching the debate tomorrow:

1. People who understand that huge, sweeping changes to the left are incredibly difficult while lurching to the far right is easy because building is much harder than destruction. These people will be holding their breath for Hillary to stomp Trump into the ground so we can keep building on the last 8 years of progress even if the pace is slower than they'd like.

2. People who have grown up with instant gratification as a given and, being new to politics, cannot fathom that they didn't get what they wanted. They invented easily-disproved fairy tales of rigged elections and warmongering to justify their rage at losing. These people will be hoping for Hillary to trip and fall so they can crow about how they were right. It will never once cross their minds that every progressive cause they profess to believe in will suffer setbacks measured in -decades- under a Trump presidency.

3. People who used to understand that politics was about compromise and that making perfect the enemy of the good was a fool's errand. But they have internalized 25 years of Anti-Clinton propaganda so deeply they honestly think she's uniquely corrupt and dishonest. These people have rejected the core premise of liberalism, basing our views on facts instead of feelings, in order to maintain a false belief in the face of mountains of evidence proving them utterly wrong. They don't care who wins because, to them, Hillary is no different than Trump.

The first group places the greater good over their own immediate needs.

The second group places their ego and hurt feelings over the greater good.

The third group has given up on the greater good because it's easier to believe the lie than to challenge their own prejudices.

Which group do you want to be in?
A well-deserved sentiment.

status_message: "Local ads from across the country have a long, storied tradition of doing crazy shit in the name of drawing eyeballs, in essence providing a certain brand of surreal comedy. This one just misfired in a very big way. That brings us back to that thorny question: Can we joke about 9/11? Yes, of course we can. I admit that while I covered 9/11 from the ground in New York City, held people in my arms who had lost loved ones, lost my weight in tears day after day, I didn't actually lose a loved one in the attacks. Maybe that disqualifies me from having an opinion. But maybe it's also true that if you believe that, it means we always have to cede every joke to those who may potentially be offended. And here's what that would mean: very little will ever be joked about, because there will always be someone, maybe even many people, who will be offended -- possibly even enraged -- by it. That kind of thing turns the whole world into a college campus, with everything trigger warning-labeled and scrubbed clean so that no one is ever made uncomfortable."

status_message:
A few days ago, Left Wing Nation shared an article from The Daily Banter writer Lenny DeFranco concerning Hillary Clinton.

To be blunt, it was a ridiculous attempt to blame Hillary and Bill Clinton for the numerous fabricated "scandals" Republicans, aided by an all too willing "liberal" media, have been pushing for decades.

I read it and had to restrain myself from deleting it on the spot. 

Once upon a time, I asked (nagged, actually) TDB's creator Ben Cohen to start sharing his site's articles on this page because we had a larger audience and I wanted all of you to experience their sharp and insightful writing. TDB shaped a good deal of my own thinking about politics and one of their writers, Bob Cesca is literally the reason I started writing 6 years ago.

TDB is a quality site that I have put a lot of trust in over the years. To say that I was disappointed in the obnoxious tone and factual inaccuracies of the Clinton article is an understatement.

status_message:
If you'll recall, when Gardasil first came out, Republicans and the religious right threw a hissy fit over it. They hated the idea of this vaccine and tried to make it seem like it was dangerous.

And why did they do this? Because it made sex safer.

Think about that for a second: The awesomeness that is science created a vaccine that cut the rate of cervical cancer in half and conservatives wanted to ban it because it removed the risk of getting cancer from a sexually transmitted disease.

In their sick minds, cervical cancer was a GOOD thing because it would punish women for having sex.

Every now and then, someone asks me why I'm so mean to the right wing. Why can't I tone it down? Why can't I try to reason with them? My answer is usually that there is no reasoning with people this far down the rabbit hole.

Conservatives have so divorced themselves from the real life consequences of their ideology, they are capable of cheering for cancer and insisting they're pro-life IN THE SAME BREATH.

Conservatism has become little more than a death cult and until we stamp out the extremism that has infested it, there can be no reasoning with them. 

There are not two legitimate sides to the question of reducing cervical cancer. There is the side that says "Yes! Saving lives is the highest possible good." and then there's the side that says "No! HPV is a useful tool to push my religious objection to sex." That's insanity and cannot be allowed to become "normal."
link_name: A decade on, vaccine has halved cervical cancer rate - BBC News

I've seen a curious reaction from far left Hillary haters as the list of Republicans and conservatives that are announcing they'll be voting for Hillary continues to grow. They've taken it as "proof" that Hillary is just a Republican pretending to be a liberal.

These people are dangerously stupid.

In their confused and addled minds, conservatives and Republicans are voting for Hillary because they actually support her. Since Hillary Clinton is the single most hated individual on the right and has been for decades, no one can honestly believe this and still expect to be taken seriously.

The reality is twofold: First, we're seeing a temporary suspension of the right wing's reflexive opposition to anything a Democrat says. Republicans and conservative talking heads have spent decades lying to their followers about the evils of all things Hillary and liberal but that was because their own agenda was so aggressively anti-99%. But push comes to shove, they know that while Hillary won't do much to advance their goals, she'll also keep the country running and safe.

Second, Republicans and conservative talking heads clearly recognize, apparently more so than far left Hillary haters, that Trump is an existential threat to the country, if not the world. Not only would he tear the country apart on a social level, he would set it on fire economically while quite possible starting a nuclear war because he was insulted on Twitter. 

In the face of such lunacy, Republicans and right wing talking heads are choosing self-preservation over suicidal ideology. 

Meanwhile, the far left is still on the deck of the Titanic screeching that getting in the lifeboat with Republicans is just as bad as freezing to death in the water and they're trying to punch holes in the lifeboats to prove it. 

This is why I treat the far left like dirt. The whiny self-defeating narcissism and rancid need for ideological purity is incompatible with real world progress and they're little better than nihilists.

I can't possibly defend a religion that expressly requires women to hide their "shameful, slutty" bodies, while Muslim men, on the other hand, are allowed to wear regular street clothes -- the same men who gender-exclusively hand down the b*llshit, dark ages penalties that include the world's most horrendous punishments.

status_message:
If Hillary Clinton did absolutely nothing for 8 years but keep the country stable while the Republican Party violently collapses, she would be a successful president.

Fortunately, she'll do more than hold the line. She's going to solidify Obama's legacy and build on that rock solid foundation.
 
Unfortunately, being the nerdy as fuck wonk that she is, a lot of what she's going to do will be quiet and obscure stuff that people either don't understand or don't WANT to understand because it doesn't fit on a bumper sticker.

For example, if the phrase "Strategically Important Financial Institutions" makes your eyes roll back into your head in boredom, then you cannot possibly understand how important the Dodd-Frank Wall Street reform bill is. And that's one of the easier aspects of it to understand.

We live in a big, complicated country and not every fix is going to be big and obvious with a catchy name. Sometimes, even the smallest tweak can make all the difference in the world. And while Obama is a smart guy, Clinton was born to do this kind of work.

She may not give the most rousing speeches or fire up the country, but if we let her do her job, in 8 years we're going to be saying "We're better off than we were 8 years ago. But how? How the hell did she do all of that without anyone noticing?"

"While this larger, more thoughtful strategy needs to be put into place to undermine the tenants of the Republican's destructive nihilism, there is an immediate and present danger in the form of Donald Trump, and all efforts must be directed towards bringing him down by any means necessary. Happy Birthday, Mr. President!

You took office almost 8 years ago in the middle of an economic disaster and faced absolute 100% obstruction from Republicans.

Despite several missteps and a lot of time wasted trying to reason with a party that had abandoned any pretense of bipartisanship, you rescued the economy without relying on an unstable bubble, helped tens of millions of Americans get healthcare for the first time in their lives, vastly reduced our military involvement in the Middle East, resisted the false promise of austerity, negotiated a treaty with Iran instead of going to war over nothing, saved the American auto industry which is now thriving, made college loans a whole lot cheaper, restored the world's confidence in America, successfully raised two daughters, avoided every Republican attempt to create a scandal, dramatically increased our power to limit Wall Street's greed, advanced the cause of LGBT rights more than every other president combined and most of all, you gave us hope that we CAN escape the legacy of greed and hate that was Ronald Reagan's vile gift to America.

I hear a lot of people complain that Hillary Clinton is just going to be more of the same; just Obama's third term. To that I say, Jesus fucking Christ, I hope so!

So Happy Birthday, Mr. President. You will go down in the history books as one of the greatest presidents in our nation's history. My great grandchildren will read about what you did and know that you and those you inspired to build on your legacy are the reason they and everyone they know have universal healthcare, a good job, a safe home and no worries about where the will be left to fend for themselves in their old age.

You won. America won. The world won. The haters lost. Ha. Ha. Ha.

status_message: "Let's just skip right to the point here: There aren't enough hyperbolic adjectives to truly and properly express just how big a deal it is that Russia is almost certainly behind the hack of the Democratic National Committee and that the goal of that hack was likely to throw the presidential election for Donald Trump. If you can't fully comprehend the magnitude of what we're talking about, go back and read that sentence again. status_message:
In Dave Chapelle's famous Rick James skit, there's a line where "Rick James" is yelling at the Murphy brothers, "Wide nose havin' muthafuckers!" and it's funny as hell in the context of the skit.

But when I hear it coming out of a cop's mouth right before the murder of a black man for the crime of being black, it makes my skin crawl. Then I hear people say that there's no racism in the police force and I wonder exactly how many cops they have to hear talk like this and see behave like this and how many stories of black people being harassed, beaten or killed they have to read about and see how many cops get away with it before they stop pretending that there's nothing wrong.

The problem is not just that the police are implicitly, if not explicitly, racist; it's also that they rarely pay a penalty for that racism. If you know that you can indulge your prejudice and abuse your power without consequence, there's absolutely no incentive to be responsible. Had a bad day? Pull over a wide nose havin' muthafucker and kick their ass! What's he going to do? Call the police? Got an itchy trigger finger? Just say you thought he was reaching for a gun after telling him to get his ID. No jury will convict! Is some black bitch giving you lip after your wife didn't put out last night? Slap her around a bit and rape her! No one is going to take the word of a black woman over an upstanding officer of the law!

If you don't think there are tens of thousands of cops that think just like this, you're worse than naive: You're willfully blind and almost certainly not black. Enjoy wallowing in your privilege while minorities are systematically raped, beaten and murdered using your tax dollars.

status_message:
I know there are still people on my page who refuse to believe white privilege exists so I want you to do the following mental exercise:

Replace the black guy in this latest cop murder with a white guy. Same car, same neighborhood, same cop, hell, even give him the same black girlfriend.

Now have this white guy tell the cop that he is licensed to carry a gun and that he is, in fact, armed and that he's getting his ID from his pocket as instructed by the officer.

Now, here's the tricky part: Reproduce the scenario where the cop pulls his gun and kills the white guy for obeying his orders. Does it feel like something that would be likely to happen? Or does it feel like you had to stretch your imagination as if part of your mind refuses to believe it would be that easy for a cop to blow away a white guy for no reason whatsoever?

That gap between how easy it is for your mind to accept what actually happened and how difficult it is to imagine the same thing happening to a white person in identical circumstances? That, my friend, is white privilege.

status_message: "When it comes to politics, young people throughout recent history have been easy to energize but have also proven notoriously difficult to actually get to the polls. There are some understandable reasons for this, like the fact that young people tend to be moving from place to place more, with their days consumed by odd work hours and other concerns older voters simply don't have. There are also, however, some predictably dubious reasons for this, like the fact that kids love the thrill of rallies and 'rock star' spectacles, where they can join with others just like them and feel like they're part of something empowering, trendy and 'cool,' but when the time comes to do the actual work, well, they just have better things to do. (Those cynical about Millennials in particular could joke that since they couldn't, like, vote by Snapchat, too much was being asked of them.) Or they figure, wrongly, that so many people like them showed up at the rally -- or are continuing to reinforce their bubble online -- that their one non-vote won't matter. When you get enough people who think that way -- that's how a candidate loses and loses badly."
link_name: Surprise: Bernie Sanders's Youth Revolution Loved Rallies More Than Actually Voting

status_message: "What was once an all but insurmountable path to the nomination for Bernie Sanders is now an impossible path. It's no path at all. For Sanders to actually attempt to make the case that the superdelegates he so forcefully excoriated as undemocratic should be truly undemocratic and abandon the winning candidate would be a pathetic kind of irony. If he genuinely tries to do this, he seals the legacy of his candidacy: It will be remembered as arrogance and folly, as the madness of a petulant man-child rather than the noble work of a dedicated public servant committed to positive change. Not only would the attempted thwarting of Hillary Clinton and the Democrats' efforts to take the presidency and stop Trump be unconscionable at face value and a potential threat to the country and the world, they would be rewarded with an effective end to Sanders's career in the Senate. Sanders relies on Democratic patronage and he needs allies in Congress in order to have any sort of successful impact on his state and the American people. To spit in the faces of the Democrats would turn Sanders into a pariah. He'd be banished to a kind of political Siberia -- and make no mistake, he would deserve it."
link_name: It's Over, Bernie. You Didn't Win. It's Time To Concede.

status_message: "Here's the really entertaining part about this little Cenk/Stelter confrontation: Cenk is being an astonishing hypocrite during the whole damn thing. Like Bernie Sanders himself, Cenk deep down believes the superdelegate system is only fair when its votes are going in the direction of a candidate he approves of. Case in point, not long after CNN dust-up, Peter Daou of Blue Nation Review began circulating an old piece of video that's a must-see complement to Cenk's indignant rant against Brian Stelter. In the clip, from 2008, Cenk rails on about how obscene it is that Hillary Clinton's campaign, under the leadership of loathsome turd Mark Penn, dismisses the importance of Barack Obama's victories in certain states and, yes, claims that it plans to challenge Obama's claim to superdelegates regardless of who wins the popular vote. He slams outright the notion of a campaign saying it's willing to defy the will of the voters to try to convince superdelegates to jump ship from the winner. About this, Cenk says, 'Who doesn't look at that and go, 'These are the bad guys; I can't support these guys?''"

status_message: "Look, devoting a lot of time to Susan Sarandon is probably a waste. She's way too far gone to bring back to reality and, let's be honest, who gives a fuck what she thinks anyway? But there's still something inherently offensive about someone of her immense wealth and privilege holding court about the beauty of 'the revolution' and, basically, the necessity of breaking a few eggs to make that perfect omelette. (With those eggs being the little people who'd actually suffer and potentially die in an America controlled by Trump.) As I've said before, it's a breeze to extoll the dream of a left-wing utopia and the potentially heavy collateral damage needed to make it so when you're not the one on the firing line. I mean, why should she be concerned about a wall separating the U.S. and Mexico or the fate of Muslims under a Trump administration when none of it would impact her in the slightest? Still, the outrageous self-appointed entitlement it takes to stand on the edge of the arena and give the thumbs up or down to those who don't have the luxury of being insulated from catastrophe, all so your great revolution can finally come to fruition -- it's fucking unconscionable."
link_name: Time for Yet Another Episode of "What Stupid F*cking Thing Did Susan Sarandon Say Now?"

status_message: "Is it possible the mother of the child who fell into Harambe's habitat on Saturday was thoroughly irresponsible and that's what set this unfortunate incident into motion? Hell, not only is it possible, it's pretty likely. But before we decide that a couple of people -- or one person, since we don't even know if both parents were there at the time -- need to be put up against a wall behind the Hague, shouldn't we determine, you know, what actually happened? And before anyone says what so many are saying: 'Yeah, but a good parent never loses track of her kid!!' well, bullshit. It's one thing to forget or not realize your child is in a carseat literally two feet behind you and lock him in an oven for eight hours; it's another thing entirely to take a four-year-old to the chaos of a busy zoo on a Saturday and have him scamper off while you're overloaded, leaving you turning in circles for a moment trying to find him (potentially, enough time for him to crawl past an animal enclosure). We don't know if the parents had other children they were dealing with. We don't know how long the child was out of their sight. We hardly know a damn thing, and yet so many are willing to sanctimoniously pass judgment and decide punishment."
link_name: "Shoot the Parents" and Other Insane Responses To the Killing of a Gorilla

status_message: "Donald Trump is, rather, the embodiment of every quality decent parents caution their children against. We tell kids not to be vain. No one is more vain and self-obsessed than Trump. We tell them to be honest. Trump is, again, someone who lies constantly and without an ounce of shame. We tell them to treat others with respect. Trump is an abusive bully who insults and belittles those around him in the name of making himself seem more important, a chauvinist who reduces women to either sex objects or pigs, and a nativist who preaches white, American supremacy. We tell children to work hard for what they want. Trump was born with everything and has done little to achieve his success other than ultimately parlay his name into a self-serving brand. If we're good parents, we tell them that sacrifice is noble in the service of governance. Trump has never sacrificed a thing. If by some unimaginable catastrophe he wins, he'll be the least qualified president in our nation's history, a man who not only has zero experience governing but who has never even for a moment served any cause other than Donald Trump."

status_message: "Late Tuesday night, Sanders's victory speech in Oregon gave away the plot. He had just won the state by about six points, with Clinton eking out a win in Kentucky for an utterly inconsequential net gain in delegates for Sanders. He's still on track to lose; taking Oregon didn't change that at all, as none of his victories have since March 15th. Yet his speech was as insanely mutinous as his earlier statement on Nevada, with a fiery Sanders painting the Democratic Party as corrupt if it wasn't willing to let the people in. As Josh Marshall at Talking Points Memo reports today, it spoke volumes about Sanders's thinking. 'Sanders narrative today has essentially been that he *is* political legitimacy,' Marshall writes. "The Democratic party needs to realize that." Marshall's overall point: that according to his sources -- and Marshall is one of the best in the business -- the hostility and toxicity in Sanders's campaign is coming straight from the top. From Sanders himself. He's lying to his supporters, telling them he can win when he can't. And if he can't, he's telling them that the election is being stolen. This is where we are now."

"At the end of 'Amadeus,' after Salieri finishes his lengthy, dramatic 
confession of all he did to destroy the career and life of his rival, Mozart, the movie cuts away to the reaction of the priest he's speaking to. The man's head comes up slowly from his hands and the expression on his face is absolutely priceless, conveying in a single look exhaustion, horror, desperation, helplessness and no small amount of bewilderment. If you translated it into spoken English the result would likely be, 'Dear God in heaven, what in the fuck was that?' Well, that's how I feel right now. That look the priest gives Salieri? status_message: "The question now, as attention turns to the general election, is how loudly and often the political press will point out these undeniable facts about Donald Trump. The thing about Trump is that he's given them so much material to work with that all they need to do is hold that up for the audience to see, over and over again, or better yet hold it up for Trump and force him to explain himself. What remains to be seen is whether they'll do it -- whether they'll adhere tightly to their responsibility to journalism and the nation as well as feel the need to confront a serial liar who makes a mockery of the very job they do and the central tenet of it, which is to find the truth."

status_message: "There will always be artists who stand out from the crowd, but it's hard to imagine, kind of like Bowie, that there will ever be another Prince. The man simply had *too much* talent. Like Bowie, it didn't seem like he was of this earth. And given the state of music in the year 2016, we should be clamoring for more of what he represented, not settling for less. The death of Prince at the unforgivable age of only 57 is devastating not only because of his tremendous output, his peerless gifts as an artist, and his mere presence as a musical true north in the world, but because the very super-connected, endlessly fragmented culture that's rendered hyperbole so common has also removed the society-spanning shadow of people like him. Put simply, it's almost impossible to be a mythical, world-shaking god in music anymore. But that fact merely suggests how important it is to have people like that walking among us: larger than life beings who operate on an entirely different plane of artistic brilliance."
link_name: We Couldn't Afford To Lose Prince

No, as of yet Sanders's acolytes haven't physically hurt anyone, but their manic devotion to their candidate has created an ugly atmosphere and physical violence isn't the only way to behave thuggishly. Just ask some of those Democratic superdelegates, who claim to now be on the receiving end of harassment and threats, often tinged with misogyny, aimed at getting them to change their votes over to Sanders. (Again, that's not going to happen, and if anyone doing this thinks it's the best way to get someone to look upon Sanders as a more favorable choice, they're obviously out-to-lunch.) Between that and Sanders's own insinuation that his campaign might seek to subvert the will of the voters when it comes time for the superdelegates to throw in their votes -- poaching from states he didn't even win, which he once decried as undemocratic -- and we have an election cycle dominated by the extremes on both the right and the left."

status_message: "In some ways, sane people this election cycle -- the few fighting to be heard amidst the sound and fury of the extremes -- owe Susan Sarandon a serious debt of gratitude on this one. There are those who see the "Bernie or Bust" movement as strictly an internet phenomenon, one promoted only by impressionable kids who probably won't vote anyway, but Sarandon has just elevated it and given a face to it. And, as it turns out, it's the face of L'Oreal, a face attached to an Oscar-winning actress and member of Hollywood royalty. In case that isn't enough to point out the laughable irony of Sarandon's apparent willingness to throw the country under the bus, let's make it crystal clear: Susan Sarandon is as privileged an individual as they come, someone almost certainly insulated from whatever catastrophes the country might experience under a President Trump, and yet she sees no problem leaving the rest of us plebes to drown. She's the prime example of the moral bankruptcy of those claiming that a Trump presidency would actually be good for the country in the long run -- because she's not the one who'll have to sacrifice to achieve her dream of a democratic socialist utopia."
link_name: Susan Sarandon Is a Privileged Idiot

status_message: "Ragging on American beer, and Budweiser in particular if only for its ubiquity, is practically a pastime among the urbanite set. Oh sure, hipsters will drink the shit out of PBR without even thinking twice because for some inexplicable reason there's vintage cultural cachet in that. (Pair it with Tater Tots and it makes every asshole with an usual mustache and a closet full of plaid shirts feel like he's just spent a long day on the assembly line rather than a casual afternoon thumbing through import vinyl in Williamsburg.) But Bud just doesn't carry with it any sort of ironically lo-fi prestige. It's a standard beer made by a big domestic company, a beer with a long history and an easy association with working class America. So why is one beloved by Millennials while another is shunned? The answer is probably that for decades Budweiser has continued to be inextricably tied to sports and popular culture, and therefore "mainstream," while Pabst had to fade into obscurity so that it could be revived by douchebags who'd feel like they were drinking something unusual."
link_name: Budweiser Tastes Like Beer. What the Hell Else Do You Want?

status_message: "Now certainly, Bernie Sanders isn't a budding fascist demagogue and a genuine threat to our country and its democracy. But by shouting his name during their push to shut down Trump's rally last week, Sanders's young supporters made it seem like his campaign is simply the left-wing answer to Trump's. No doubt that's why the protest's organizers initially wanted to keep their action independent and not attached to any one particular Trump challenger: because the message needed to be that Trump was a genuine threat to our nation and its people rather than, 'Trump's dangerous, here's the alternative! Feel the Bern!' In fact, by making it seem as if Trump's detractors were all agents of Bernie Sanders, Sanders's supporters gave Trump an easy out and the perfect target to deflect criticism onto in the wake of the brawl. He's already blamed "communist" Bernie for wrecking his rally and quashing his First Amendment rights. (One more time for the cheap seats: the First Amendment doesn't protect you from protesters exercising their First Amendment rights.) Trump never should've had a specific villain he could sic his idiot rabble on because the people who stopped his rally should've been, you know, *the people.*"
link_name: Warring Trump and Sanders Supporters Welcome Us To Political Extremist Hell

status_message: "The last time political nihilists tried to convince us both parties were the same and that a political uprising was necessary to shake everything up -- because as my detractor says, 'it's the rigged system, stupid' -- we got 4,448 dead Americans in Iraq and countless Iraqis. We got 1,856 Americans dead Afghanistan and more than 20,000 wounded. We got 9/11, which started it all, because the idiot we figured was just like the other guy was too incurious to read his daily briefings. The two parties are not the same. They've never been the same. Anyone who says so needs to be willing to join the U.S. military immediately, particularly with the prospect of a President Donald Trump. Because while no one knows the future, here's what Hillary Clinton won't do: she won't go to war with Liechtenstein because the country's prince insulted her fingers. I'm exaggerating, but honestly by how much? We know that Clinton won't attempt to round up and deport 11 million people. She won't roll back civil rights advances, abortion rights, or health insurance coverage for millions. She won't appoint Supreme Court justices that will undo myriad progressive achievements. She won't build a giant, unnecessary wall along our southern border and get into an international dick-swinging contest about who's going to pay for it. She won't ban Muslims and encourage anyone to 'rough them up.' We can be reasonably sure she won't utterly ruin the United States' standing in the eyes of the world."
link_name: It's Time To Mercilessly Shame Any Liberal Threatening To Let Donald Trump Win

status_message: "MSNBC is indeed corporate media. As such it's interested in two things: objectively reporting events to the best of its ability and honoring its bottom line. The latter of those is an unfortunate fact of life and it can absolutely come into conflict with the former, but that's how it is. MSNBC was never going to be Melissa Harris-Perry's one-woman bullhorn because she was never the one in charge -- NBC News was and is -- and there would always be network considerations far beyond the issues most important to her. And that's really the key here: MSNBC is a network. The last time it was anyone's personal soapbox, and that person was adamant about it being that, he was fired unceremoniously. This is how NBC News wants it and this is how it is. That should've been obvious to Harris-Perry coming in since, despite a short-lived period of experimentation with its red-headed cable stepchild, NBC News's reputation for straight news is baked into the walls of 30 Rock. And NBC News is in charge of MSNBC."
link_name: Melissa Harris-Perry Goes To War with MSNBC, the Network That Was Never Supposed To Be Liberal

status_message: "Melissa Harris-Perry is an undeniably smart person whose show is often admirably wonky and culturally incisive. Like nearly every other second string player at a large network, though, fairly or unfairly she's found herself occasionally neglected by management -- at the very least not shown the kind of respect she maybe thinks she deserves. No one could blame her if she found this a little irritating. Everybody subjected to it does. Everybody not a marquee talent in TV news has tales of being disregarded, preempted, and generally undervalued, and that's the excuse they use for why they're angrily beating down their agents' doors and slowly drinking themselves to death. The thing is, nobody makes a huge public stink about it because the news business is tough and it's a given that you're going to get ridden hard and to the point of utter frustration by sometimes clueless suits. Well, usually nobody makes a huge public stink about it."

status_message: "There are indeed serious issues out there, ones that specifically impact Millennials and would need to be confronted by either Democrat as president. Yet if we're to believe The Atlantic, many of the young people vociferously supporting Sanders, collegiate and otherwise, don't question him on those issues; they simply have a vague notion of Sanders as the 'most liberal' person running. More than that, though, they've created a cult of personality around Sanders and have turned him into a kind of weirdo folk hero: the guy with the wild hair and the Brooklyn accent who preaches fiery sermons about how they're being kept down and it's time to rise up. He listens to them and empowers them, so they reward him with their loyalty and idolatry, making them far more like Donald Trump's outraged acolytes than they'd like to admit. And sure, a vote is a vote, but in the end it's support awarded for largely superficial reasons, even if, ironically, they flock to Sanders for his 'authenticity.' They've made Bernie 'cool' and that's a self-fulfilling prophecy in which students exponentially adopt Sanders as their candidate because, well, that's just what you do when you're a member of the collegiate left in 2016. It's what everyone does."
link_name: The Kids Are for Bernie Sanders... but the Kids Are Insufferable - The Daily Banter

status_message:
When I lived in New York, my 1 year old daughter was tested for lead and had slightly elevated levels. The city tested the apartment and the paint was lead based. Three walls had to be covered and sealed.

My landlord threw a fit about it and didn't want to do it. I almost punched her in the face for daring to risk my children's health. She demanded we move out because we ended up costing her money and I spent 6 months making her life a living hell for fucking with my family.

Now imagine you live in a city where all of your water is seriously contaminated with lead and you don't have the money to move or buy fresh water every day. You were told the water was fine but now you know that irreparable damage has been done. Your child's emotional and intellectual development is permanently stunted, perhaps to the point where they will be unable to function as a productive citizen.

Now imagine that one of the political movements in the country told you to stop crying about it. It's not really a crisis and you should stop asking for government hand outs you lazy moochers.

Why? Because admitting that a Republican governor was the cause of the disaster is intolerable to them.

That is where America is right now.

We are witnessing a political movement in the final stages of sundering all ties to reality. They are crushing every last ember of empathy for people that do not fit their desired template. No lie is too big or narrative too ridiculous for them to believe as long as it reinforces their view of moral and racial superiority. History itself is clay to be reworked to absolve them of any and all responsibility for the state of the world.

What do you think this movement is going to do when it is finally forced to confront the reality that history has passed it by and they no longer control the universe? That power has passed from them to the people they despise on a genetic level? 

Will they go quietly into that good night? Will they adapt their worldview? Will they grow up? Or, more likely, will they violently lash out at their "oppressors" and leave a growing pile of bodies as they fight a "patriotic" war to "take their country back?"

Well look at that! We FINALLY found a set of circumstances in which a cop can't claim he was afraid for his life: You have to be completely naked and unarmed with witnesses.

Let's be honest, it was only a 50-50 chance this cop would be indicted and there's very little chance he'll be convicted.

We have trained out police to be absolute fucking cowards, unwilling to take even the slightest risk. We have trained them to view the public as a constant threat to their lives and then empowered them to kill without consequence.

This does not create "peace officers", it creates terrified authoritarians with a license to bully, harass and murder at will.

status_message:
Even though I'm an filthy liberal atheist (with a Jewish mother), I was raised to celebrate Christmas. Not as a religious holiday, but as a celebration of family and friends.

Consider it "cultural appropriation" but people from all walks of life and faiths celebrate Christmas the same way I do: More or less void of its original, religious meaning. Then again, considering Christmas was, itself, appropriated from older religions, I feel exactly no shame in this.

But as we gather with our loved ones to exchange gifts and eat delicious food and drink copious amounts of alcohol (no, seriously, tie one on for me), please keep in mind all of those who can only celebrate the holidays with a paucity of security, accommodations and food.

In the richest nation that has ever existed in the history of the human race, 15 million children suffer from food insecurity. This is only possible because we have allowed the culture and economy of our nation to be corrupted by conservative greed and indifference.

But there is a tipping point coming in which we will take great strides away from the societal deformation of the past 35 years. But those who benefit from that greed will not give up their obscene wealth and power without a fight and they have millions of useful idiots ready to declare war on the minority du jour to keep us distracted.

Even as you hold your family and friends close to you in a warm home, look to a future where EVERYONE has the privilege to celebrate in safety and comfort. And be ready to fight for it because if you want it, you'll have to.

- Happy Holidays from the Left Wing Nation

status_message:
As I sit here looking at my 5-year-old daughter sleeping in a warm bed with a belly full of cinnamon buns after having minor surgery that's covered by our medical insurance, it occurs to me that there are tens of thousands of little children just like her fleeing Syria. 

They do not have a warm bed.
They do not have enough food, much less cinnamon buns.
They do not have basic medicine, much less the opportunity to see a surgeon.
They do not have clean water.
They do not have warm clothes.
They do not have safety.
Many of them do not even have parents anymore.

These are the people that Republicans would have us fear and hate and reject because out of the hundreds of thousands of refugees, a few dozen, or even a few hundred, of them -might- be terrorists.

They say we should close our borders.
They say we should only let in the "good" kind of refugees.
They say we should send the rest back to certain death.
They say we should let them drown in the ocean.
They say we should shoot them if they try to cross the border.
They say that letting them in will guarantee the destruction of America.

Republicans say these things because there is a part of America that so hates and loathes anyone that is not like them that they would happily, cheerfully, joyously consign all of those child refugees to misery and death. These people, the ones that vote their hate, are also the same ones that holler their love of Jesus and the constitution from the top of their lungs.

This is not a coincidence.

In nature, we know this phenomena as camouflage: The ability to conceal your true identity. The (sizable) part of the American right wing that pretends to worship America and Jesus would, if given the opportunity, turn this country into a mirror image of the sectarian violence of the Middle East. They despise the fact that America is a nation of immigrants. They despise Jesus' message of love and tolerance. They despise the freedom for people to live lives outside of what they consider "proper."

The Republican Party is now the dominion of these monsters. If you think I'm being hyperbolic and cruel, you have not been listening carefully to what Republicans say. If you think, "That's just campaign rhetoric!" then you are blind to a very simple fact: Their rhetoric is designed to appeal to the people that will vote for them. By definition, that means the people that control the direction of the party are people who are so devoid of basic humanity that the death of children makes them feel better about themselves.

Go ahead, tell me again how both parties are the same. Say it out loud: "Democrats and Republicans are just as bad as each other. Sure, Republicans openly advocate for the death of children but that doesn't matter because they both cater to corporations." Go on, say it out loud and look at yourself in the mirror while you do it so you can see what a scumbag looks and sounds like.

I'm going to go back to watching my daughter sleep and thank the stars that I have a conscience.

status_message:
I'm listening to a podcast about the school to prison pipeline and I have to thank my lucky stars that A. I'm white and B. I went to elementary school 35 years ago.

I was..ahem..a difficult student. Aside from some anger issues from a nasty divorce, I was also easily bored in class. I consistently scored in the 98th percentile on the yearly citywide tests and that was without paying much attention in school.

At one point, my teacher was so fed up with me that I was allowed to wander the school halls by myself for I don't know how many hours a week. Even so, by the time I was in fifth grade, I had been "pre-suspended" several times.

If I'd been in school today and had been black, I would have been suspended and probably expelled and, if I was REALLY lucky, arrested. Because that's how we deal with "trouble" kids today. But only if they're not white. When white kids misbehave, they're just being kids. When black kids misbehave, it's because they're little "thugs" and can't be civilized like us superior white folk.

We throw them out of class. We throw them out of school. We throw them in jail. All before their 12th birthday.

Then, we as a society wonder why these kids that we've thrown away can't be productive members of society. They had all the same opportunities, right? Must be some inherent defect in black people.

How convenient for our collective (white) conscience.

And now that people can make millions off of putting minorities in jail and keeping them there? Don't expect it to get better any time soon.

'Murika.

status_message:
If you want to know why Republicans are so panicked over the 2016 election, look no further than the monthly jobs report.

We've had over 65 months of private sector job growth, the longest since they started keeping records of it. We added 241,000 jobs last month and unemployment is down to 5%. That's 2.8% lower than when Obama took office in the middle of Bush's economic disaster. Sure, right wingers desperate to spin will talk about the "real" unemployment figure but since we've been using the exact same metric for longer than I've been alive, absolutely no one not inside the Fox News bubble is listening to them.

Even worse, average hourly earnings are growing, a sign that the labor market is tightening. A tighter market means that corporations can't keep getting away with paying salve wages. Even worse than that, the economic troubles overseas have not seriously impacted our economy.

That means unless Wall Street can manage to crash the economy again and barring any unforeseen circumstances, the economy will be accelerating quite nicely by the time Election Day 2016 rolls around and everyone will feel it.

Have you noticed that Republicans haven't been focusing their attacks on the economy as much? It's hard to convince people the economy is still terrible when every indicator says otherwise. And without the economy to bash the Democrats with, what do Republicans have? Abortion? Gay marriage? Good luck with that.

They COULD try to tout their foreign policy bona fides but with the exception of one or two of the 0% - 1% candidates like Lindsay Graham, no one on the GOP field has ANY foreign policy experience beyond ordering Chinese take out.

Yes, Republicans cleaned up during an off-year election with record low voter turnout a couple of days ago. But it's going to be bloodbath next year all up and down the ballot and there's not a damn thing Republicans can do about it, especially if Trump or Carson or even Ted Cruz win the primaries.

status_message:
Just finished last night's Daily Show and it occurs to me that no matter what the right says, Stewart utterly defeated Fox News and the right wing media. Yes, they're still on the air and, yes, they're still a ratings juggernaut but when Stewart left, it was national news and people legitimately mourned. Stewart meant something to the country.

When O'Reilly/Hannity/Limbaugh/Beck/etc. eventually leave, it will be more like the sigh of relief when your cranky uncle leaves the room at Thanksgiving dinner. They don't mean anything deeper than the next outrage fix and there will always be another talking head spewing hate for the right to shoot into their decrepit veins.

In 50 years, history will speak of Jon Stewart in the same breath as Edward R. Murrow and Walter Cronkite. They'll speak of Fox News and the right wing media, long since relegated to the trash bin as the modern conservative movement collapses under the weight of unadulterated racism and mindless rage, in the same breath as William Randolph Hearst, Goebbels and Joe McCarthy. Nothing more than purveyors of propaganda and fear.

Stewart's legacy of critical thinking through humor and satire, in the end, will outlast the right's legacy of deceit and hatred. Count on it.

status_message:
Once upon a time, there were two little girls that lived in upper middle class upstate New York and they were BFFs. One of these girls, my niece Cassie, grew up to teach special ed children in Ohio. the other, Carla, grew up to teach underprivileged kids in one of those neighborhoods in Brooklyn that the upper middle class likes to pretend don't exist. Unsurprisingly, Carla's school is severely underfunded.

Carla is therefor running a fundraiser to provide her students with better books to read (like the Hunger Games, Lord of the Rings, Judy Blume and other amazing books), school supplies that she simply doesn't have the budget for, tablets to bring her class into the 21st century and the like.

I'm donating $75 today and I'll donate another $75 when I get paid again next month and another $75 after that until the fundraiser ends.

I know all of us understand the importance of education and how badly we need teachers with Carla's dedication. Please help her out with $10, $20 or even $50 bucks and help the next generation of students thrive!
